quran[15]{c,v,t,f}:
23,60,"who give, whatever they give in charity, with their hearts trembling at the thought that they are destined to return to their Lord; {1}",footnotes:1:This verse (60) may be elaborated like this: They serve their Lord and try their best to obey Him and do righteous deeds
23,61,"it is these who hasten to do good works and vie in so doing with one another."
23,62,"We do not lay a burden on anyone beyond his capacity. {1} We have a Book with Us that speaks the truth(about everyone) {2} ; and they shall in no wise be wronged. {3}",footnotes:1:The enunciation of this fundamental proposition
23,63,"Nay, their hearts are lost in ignorance of all this; {1} and their deeds too vary from the way (mentioned above). They will persist in these deeds",footnotes:1:They are heedless that everything they are saying and doing
23,64,"until We seize with Our chastisement those of them that are given to luxuriant ways. {1} They will then begin to groan. {2}",footnotes:1:The epicureans will probably be punished in this worldly life because in the enjoyment of luxury and pleasure they forgot the rights of the other people and transgressed the prescribed limits.|179450:Juar is bellowing by a bull painfully. Here the word has been used tauntingly for a groaning person who does not deserve any mercy
23,65,""Put<sup foot_note="179451">1</sup> a stop to your groaning now! Surely no help shall be provided to you from Us.",footnotes:1:That is
23,66,"My Signs were rehearsed to you and you turned back on your heels and took to flight, {1}",footnotes:1:That is to say
23,67,"behaving arrogantly, and making fun,"{1} and talking nonsense (about the Book in your nightly chats).",footnotes:1:The meeting places where the people of Makkah gathered together at night to hold consultations
23,68,"Did they never ponder over this Word {1} (of God)? Or has he (to wit, the Messenger) brought something the like of which did not come to their forefathers {2} of yore?",footnotes:1:That is
23,69,"Or is it that they were unaware of their Messenger and were therefore repelled by him for he was a stranger to them? {1}",footnotes:1:That is
23,70,"Or do they say that there is madness in him? {1} Nay, he has brought them the Truth and it is the Truth that most of them disdain.",footnotes:1:That is
23,71,"Were the Truth to follow their desires, the order of the heavens and the earth and those who dwell in them would have been ruined. {1} Nay, the fact is that We have brought to them their own remembrance; and yet it is from their own remembrance that they are turning away. {2}",footnotes:1:This brief sentence expresses a great reality which should be understood well. The foolish people in the world generally feel offended by a person who points out the truth to them. They do not like to hear and consider the truth because it goes against their desires and interests but the truth remains the truth and cannot be changed after one's personal whims and wishes. Man is subject to the eternal and unalterable laws operating in the universe and has therefore to adjust his thinking
23,72,"Are you asking them for something? What Allah has given you is the best. He is the Best of providers. {1}",footnotes:1:This was yet another proof of the Prophet’s (peace be upon him) Prophethood. He was conveying the message without demanding any recompense for it
23,73,"You are calling them to a Straight Way,"
23,74,"but those who do not believe in the Hereafter are ever prone to deviate from the Right Way. {1}",footnotes:1:This was the real reason why they were deviating from the right path. As they did not believe in the Hereafter
